00:00:07.430 --> 00:00:13.700
PROFESSOR: All right, an
announcement that I must make,

00:00:13.700 --> 00:00:16.690
after developing all these
friendships and working

00:00:16.690 --> 00:00:20.350
together, we will, next Tuesday,
once again, enter a

00:00:20.350 --> 00:00:22.570
brief adversarial
relationship.

00:00:22.570 --> 00:00:26.340
And we will have quiz
number two.

00:00:26.340 --> 00:00:31.970
What we will cover on that
quiz will be about 50%,

00:00:31.970 --> 00:00:35.330
perhaps a little bit
more, on symmetry.

00:00:35.330 --> 00:00:37.630
And I'll remind you in just a
minute what we've covered

00:00:37.630 --> 00:00:39.220
since the last quiz.

00:00:39.220 --> 00:00:45.180
And the second half or 40% of
the quiz will be on the

00:00:45.180 --> 00:00:48.550
formalism of tensors and
tensor manipulation.

00:00:48.550 --> 00:00:50.390
And obviously, you've
had a chance only to

00:00:50.390 --> 00:00:52.090
do a very few problems.

00:00:52.090 --> 00:00:55.620
So these will be pretty basic
questions and nothing tricky

00:00:55.620 --> 00:00:57.280
or very difficult.

00:00:57.280 --> 00:01:00.460
So let me remind you very, very
quickly just by topics

00:01:00.460 --> 00:01:01.810
what we've covered.

00:01:01.810 --> 00:01:06.950
We began the period following
the first quiz discussing how

00:01:06.950 --> 00:01:10.440
we can take the plane groups,
two-dimensional symmetries

00:01:10.440 --> 00:01:13.720
that are translationally
periodic, and defining a third

00:01:13.720 --> 00:01:18.590
translation to stack up the
plane groups to give us a

00:01:18.590 --> 00:01:22.140
three-dimensional periodic

00:01:22.140 --> 00:01:24.030
arrangement of symmetry elements.

00:01:24.030 --> 00:01:28.580
In doing so, we found that
we had to pick that third

00:01:28.580 --> 00:01:32.360
translation such that the
symmetry elements that were in

00:01:32.360 --> 00:01:35.080
the plane group, and those were
the things that made the

00:01:35.080 --> 00:01:38.780
lattices of the plane groups
special, made them square or

00:01:38.780 --> 00:01:42.340
hexagonal or rectangular, that
was true because there was

00:01:42.340 --> 00:01:43.260
symmetry there.

00:01:43.260 --> 00:01:47.210
Once again, symmetry and the
specialness of a lattice are

00:01:47.210 --> 00:01:49.870
two inseparable parts
of the story.

00:01:49.870 --> 00:01:52.160
But if we did this,
the symmetry

00:01:52.160 --> 00:01:53.960
elements had to coincide.

00:01:53.960 --> 00:01:57.380
Otherwise, we would reproduce
new symmetry elements in the

00:01:57.380 --> 00:01:59.740
base of the cell and
wreck everything.

00:01:59.740 --> 00:02:02.160
So when we did that, there were
a very limited number of

00:02:02.160 --> 00:02:03.410
ways of doing it.

00:02:07.020 --> 00:02:11.420
In the course of doing that,
we fell headlong over screw

00:02:11.420 --> 00:02:15.400
axis in the same way that we
fell over glide planes as soon

00:02:15.400 --> 00:02:20.390
as we put mirror lines in a
two-dimensional lattice.

00:02:20.390 --> 00:02:24.910
The interesting thing was that
that exercise of stacking the

00:02:24.910 --> 00:02:28.580
two-dimensional plane groups
gave us almost all of the

00:02:28.580 --> 00:02:31.610
lattice types that exist
in three dimensions.

00:02:31.610 --> 00:02:34.080
And the reason for that is we
showed very directly that

00:02:34.080 --> 00:02:36.020
inversion requires nothing.

00:02:36.020 --> 00:02:39.100
So therefore, any of the point
groups that were used in

00:02:39.100 --> 00:02:42.210
deriving the plane groups, when
augmented by inversion to

00:02:42.210 --> 00:02:45.080
give a three-dimensional point
group, are going to require

00:02:45.080 --> 00:02:48.000
nothing more than the lattices
that we derived by stacking

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:49.240
the plane groups.

00:02:49.240 --> 00:02:52.800
And that took care of just about
everything except for

00:02:52.800 --> 00:02:54.650
the cubic symmetries.

00:02:54.650 --> 00:02:57.350
And we disposed of those
in very short order.

00:02:57.350 --> 00:02:59.560
So that led us to the
14 space lattices,

00:02:59.560 --> 00:03:02.070
so-called bravais lattices.

00:03:02.070 --> 00:03:06.840
And then we proceeded to work
with those lattices and put in

00:03:06.840 --> 00:03:09.370
the point groups that could
accommodate them.

00:03:09.370 --> 00:03:12.370
Having discovered glide planes,
we then, if we had

00:03:12.370 --> 00:03:14.700
done the process systematically,
would have

00:03:14.700 --> 00:03:17.620
replaced mirror planes
by glide planes.

00:03:17.620 --> 00:03:22.810
And having discovered screw
axes, we replace pure rotation

00:03:22.810 --> 00:03:26.940
by screw axis rotations.

00:03:26.940 --> 00:03:29.780
And then doing what we did but
didn't have to do very often,

00:03:29.780 --> 00:03:33.130
mercifully, for the plane
groups, we said one could also

00:03:33.130 --> 00:03:35.350
interweave symmetry elements.

00:03:35.350 --> 00:03:39.230
And that gave a few additional
space groups.

00:03:39.230 --> 00:03:41.590
We did not derive very
many of them.

00:03:41.590 --> 00:03:44.320
What is important at this stage
is simply to realize

00:03:44.320 --> 00:03:48.420
that their properties and
applications are very similar

00:03:48.420 --> 00:03:51.850
to what we discovered for the
two-dimensional plane groups.

00:03:51.850 --> 00:03:53.730
The notation is a little
bit different.

00:03:53.730 --> 00:03:57.460
Because there can be symmetry
elements parallel to the plane

00:03:57.460 --> 00:04:00.410
of the paper so that in
depicting the arrangement of

00:04:00.410 --> 00:04:03.390
symmetry elements you need a
little [? chevron-type ?]

00:04:03.390 --> 00:04:06.830
device to indicate whether
you've got a mirror plane or a

00:04:06.830 --> 00:04:09.340
glide plane in the
base of the cell.

00:04:09.340 --> 00:04:12.360
And similarly with two-fold
axes, and that's about the

00:04:12.360 --> 00:04:15.460
only thing that would be in the
plane of the paper if the

00:04:15.460 --> 00:04:21.459
principal symmetry is normal to
the paper, we need a device

00:04:21.459 --> 00:04:24.380
for indicating the elevation
and whether the axis is a

00:04:24.380 --> 00:04:26.490
two-fold rotation
axis or a screw.

00:04:26.490 --> 00:04:29.280
So there's a geometrical
language for describing the

00:04:29.280 --> 00:04:30.930
arrangement of the
space groups.

00:04:30.930 --> 00:04:34.320
We had a few problems in
determining space group

00:04:34.320 --> 00:04:37.500
symbols and interpreting
what these mean.

00:04:37.500 --> 00:04:41.420
But again, I don't think I would
be sadistic enough to

00:04:41.420 --> 00:04:46.000
ask you to derive a complicated
three-dimensional

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:47.380
space group.

00:04:47.380 --> 00:04:47.710
I don't know.

00:04:47.710 --> 00:04:50.300
Maybe over the weekend, if I get
to feeling mean, I might

00:04:50.300 --> 00:04:51.740
ask you something in
those directions.

00:04:51.740 --> 00:04:55.150
But it will not be anything
terribly formidable.

00:04:55.150 --> 00:04:58.620
Then finally, we looked at the
way in which space groups can

00:04:58.620 --> 00:05:02.890
be used to describe
three-dimensional periodic

00:05:02.890 --> 00:05:04.100
arrays of atoms.

00:05:04.100 --> 00:05:06.560
And that again was strictly
analogous to what we did in

00:05:06.560 --> 00:05:09.070
two dimensions.

00:05:09.070 --> 00:05:13.290
The description of the
three-dimensional arrangement

00:05:13.290 --> 00:05:17.820
of atoms, particularly if it
is too complicated to be

00:05:17.820 --> 00:05:21.230
readily appreciated in a
projection, would have to be

00:05:21.230 --> 00:05:24.710
given in terms of the space
group, the type of position

00:05:24.710 --> 00:05:27.600
that is occupied, either
special or the general

00:05:27.600 --> 00:05:31.260
position, and then depending on
how many degrees of freedom

00:05:31.260 --> 00:05:34.410
are available in those positions
to give you the

00:05:34.410 --> 00:05:37.480
coordinates of the element or
just the x-coordinate or the x

00:05:37.480 --> 00:05:38.760
and y-coordinate.

00:05:38.760 --> 00:05:40.840
And then you run to the
international tables.

00:05:40.840 --> 00:05:42.840
You don't have to work
this out yourself.

00:05:42.840 --> 00:05:46.510
And you find the list of
coordinates that are related

00:05:46.510 --> 00:05:49.590
by symmetry for that particular
special position

00:05:49.590 --> 00:05:54.310
and then plug in x and y to get
all the coordinates of the

00:05:54.310 --> 00:05:55.560
atoms in the unit cell.

00:05:58.180 --> 00:06:03.380
To go to the practical aspects
of this, usually only simple

00:06:03.380 --> 00:06:10.520
structures can be projected
with any clarity that lets

00:06:10.520 --> 00:06:12.410
them be interpreted.

00:06:12.410 --> 00:06:16.640
And even with a computer these
days one can show an

00:06:16.640 --> 00:06:20.210
orthographic projection of the
structure and then in real

00:06:20.210 --> 00:06:23.850
time manipulate it so you
can see this beautiful

00:06:23.850 --> 00:06:26.770
construction with colored
shiny spheres

00:06:26.770 --> 00:06:28.550
in it rotating around.

00:06:28.550 --> 00:06:31.670
But if it's a complicated
structure, even that doesn't

00:06:31.670 --> 00:06:33.340
do you very much.

00:06:33.340 --> 00:06:36.320
It works for NaCO and
zinc sulfide.

00:06:36.320 --> 00:06:37.840
But you know what
those look like.

00:06:37.840 --> 00:06:41.450
And so you don't really need
this very attractive, real

00:06:41.450 --> 00:06:42.680
time interaction.

00:06:42.680 --> 00:06:47.167
What I found works well is to
take the structure and slice

00:06:47.167 --> 00:06:52.020
it apart in layers like a
layer cake and look at a

00:06:52.020 --> 00:06:57.590
limited range of the one
translation, generally, one of

00:06:57.590 --> 00:07:01.440
the shorter translations, and
examine the coordination of

00:07:01.440 --> 00:07:03.040
atoms within that layer.

00:07:03.040 --> 00:07:06.540
And so by slicing the structure
away and looking at

00:07:06.540 --> 00:07:09.760
it in several layers that are
stacked on top of one another,

00:07:09.760 --> 00:07:12.910
the way I work between the ears,
usually lets me gain an

00:07:12.910 --> 00:07:15.080
appreciation of what's going
on in that structure.

00:07:15.080 --> 00:07:17.530
Something different might
work for you.

00:07:17.530 --> 00:07:20.180
Matter of fact, you might be a
gifted person who can see the

00:07:20.180 --> 00:07:23.080
things spinning around on a
computer screen and understand

00:07:23.080 --> 00:07:24.040
exactly what it is.

00:07:24.040 --> 00:07:27.980
But everybody's mind works in
a slightly different way.

00:07:27.980 --> 00:07:31.740
OK, that is roughly what we'll
be covering on symmetry.

00:07:31.740 --> 00:07:34.770
Then we got into the connection
between symmetry

00:07:34.770 --> 00:07:36.760
and physical properties.

00:07:36.760 --> 00:07:43.755
And we defined what we
meant by a tensor.

00:07:43.755 --> 00:07:46.460
A tensor of the second
rank is something

00:07:46.460 --> 00:07:48.240
that relates to vectors.

00:07:48.240 --> 00:07:52.700
We got into a notation involving
the assumption that

00:07:52.700 --> 00:07:55.800
any repeated subscript, and
there's subscripts all over

00:07:55.800 --> 00:07:57.680
the place in tensor
properties.

00:07:57.680 --> 00:08:02.890
Any repeated subscript is
automatically implied to be

00:08:02.890 --> 00:08:04.525
summed over from 1 to 3.

00:08:07.580 --> 00:08:14.690
We then derived the laws for
transformation of a tensor.

00:08:14.690 --> 00:08:17.970
Namely that, if you specify
the change of coordinate

00:08:17.970 --> 00:08:24.890
system by a direction cosine
scheme, cij, where cij is the

00:08:24.890 --> 00:08:30.810
cosine of the angle between x of
i prime and x sub j, that,

00:08:30.810 --> 00:08:34.140
since these direction cosines
constitute unit vectors, there

00:08:34.140 --> 00:08:36.370
had to be relations
between them.

00:08:36.370 --> 00:08:39.830
Namely the sum of the squares
of the terms in any row or

00:08:39.830 --> 00:08:42.750
column had to be unity.

00:08:42.750 --> 00:08:46.960
The sum of corresponding terms
in any row or column

00:08:46.960 --> 00:08:48.140
had to add to 0.

00:08:48.140 --> 00:08:51.860
Because these represented dot
products of unit vectors in a

00:08:51.860 --> 00:08:54.280
Cartesian coordinate system.

00:08:54.280 --> 00:08:59.060
And then using this array of
direction cosines, we found

00:08:59.060 --> 00:09:03.970
that the way in which a second
ranked tensor transformed was

00:09:03.970 --> 00:09:09.560
that each tensor element was
given by a linear combination

00:09:09.560 --> 00:09:13.300
of all of the elements of
the original tensor.

00:09:13.300 --> 00:09:18.550
And out in front of the tensor
was a product of two direction

00:09:18.550 --> 00:09:24.920
cosines, the subscripts of which
were determined by the

00:09:24.920 --> 00:09:27.210
indices of that element.

00:09:27.210 --> 00:09:30.300
A vector could be regarded
as a first ranked tensor.

00:09:30.300 --> 00:09:32.430
And everybody understands
the law for

00:09:32.430 --> 00:09:34.000
transformation of a vector.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:36.440
Namely that each component
of the vector is a linear

00:09:36.440 --> 00:09:40.270
combination of every component
of the original vector with

00:09:40.270 --> 00:09:42.370
one direction cosine
out in front.

00:09:42.370 --> 00:09:45.590
Tensor of second rank has a
product of two direction

00:09:45.590 --> 00:09:49.080
cosines summed over all
the elements of

00:09:49.080 --> 00:09:50.330
the original tensor.

00:09:50.330 --> 00:09:52.710
Third ranked tensors, which,
believe it or not, we'll get

00:09:52.710 --> 00:09:56.340
into after the quiz in
considerable detail, and even

00:09:56.340 --> 00:09:59.310
shudder fourth ranked tensors
are going to involve

00:09:59.310 --> 00:10:04.090
summations that involve scads of
terms and products of three

00:10:04.090 --> 00:10:08.120
and four direction cosines
respectively.

00:10:08.120 --> 00:10:10.890
So we won't get very
far into tensors.

00:10:10.890 --> 00:10:16.060
We will perhaps have a couple of
questions on the nature of

00:10:16.060 --> 00:10:19.710
anisotropy that's implied
by these relations.

00:10:19.710 --> 00:10:22.940
And I think, if you looked at
the problem sets to this

00:10:22.940 --> 00:10:25.520
